# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-departure-tax
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] On 20 June 2017, the Air Departure Tax (Scotland) Act 2017 was passed in the Scottish Parliament and received royal assent on 25 July 2017 and was meant to be introduced on 1 April 2018.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] However, on 22 November 2017, the UK and Scottish ministers agreed to delay the introduction of ADT until issues have been resolved regarding the tax exemption for flights departing airports in the Highlands and Islands of Scotland.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] In June 2018, the Scottish Government and UK Government agreed that it would not be possible to introduce the ADT in April 2019.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] Air Passenger Duty has continued to apply for airports in Scotland and HMRC has continued to administer APD in relation to flights in Scotland.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] On 13 January 2026, it was announced that an alternative to maintain an exemption for the Highlands and Islands from the tax had been designed.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] The tax will now apply from 1 April 2027.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] The Scottish Government intended to reduce the rate by 50%, and eventually abolish it completely once finances allowed.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] This caused concern that such a move could damage tourism in England.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-departure-tax] However, in 2019 the Scottish Government abandoned its plans to cut Air Departure Tax as the proposals were no longer considered compatible with Scotland's climate change targets.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Air Passenger Duty was introduced in 1994 by the then chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Clarke regarded it as anomalous that fuel duty was not levied on air transport, but international agreements prevented his levying a duty on aircraft kerosene.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] As an alternative, Clarke introduced Air Passenger Duty, a levy collected by airlines on passengers who start their journeys at UK airports.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] It was initially set at £5 for European flights and £10 for long-haul flights.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Children below one year of age were exempt.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] When APD was first introduced, the return journey of a UK domestic flight was exempt from APD.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] However, this was deemed to be inconsistent with European Union competition rules.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Return flights within the UK have incurred two APD payments since 2001.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The subsequent chancellor, Gordon Brown, introduced a double rate of APD for business-class and first-class passengers.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] His successor, George Osborne, reduced the duty on the most expensive long-haul bands.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Since 2016 children below the age of 16 have been exempt from APD provided they are travelling in basic economy class.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Air Passenger Duty charges take distance into account, making long distance flying significantly more expensive.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] One of the stated benefits of APD was to offset the environmental impact of air travel (see below) although the tax takes no account of the efficiency of the aircraft and flows into general revenue.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Air passenger duty is paid upon booking, but not collected until an occupied seat flies.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Should a passenger be unable to fly they have a right to claim the paid tax back from the airline, although many airlines will charge an administrative fee for this service.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Band A includes whole Europe, Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Libya, Cyprus, Turkey and Western Russia.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] A £0 rate of APD applies to flights from Northern Ireland direct to a band B destination as of 1 November 2011.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] This is due to Continental Airlines threatening to stop the direct Belfast - Newark flight due to lack of demand because of the tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The 2021 UK budget announced changes to the levels of reduced-rate APD.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The rate for UK domestic flights is due to halve to £6.50 from April 2023, while the rate for band B is due to increase to £84 in April 2022.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] From April 2023 band B is set to be split into two bands: the rate for journeys of 2,000–5,500 miles is set to rise to £87, and the rate for journeys over 5,500 miles is set to rise to £91.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Air Passenger Duty was controversially doubled from 1 February 2007, and the lower rate was extended to all the countries within the Single European Sky.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Here, 'European destinations' includes countries in the European Economic Area and certain other European countries.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Charges rose on 1 November 2009 and again on 1 November 2010.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The Treasury forecast that the 2007 rise would cut carbon dioxide emissions by about 0.3 million tonnes a year by 2010-2011, and all greenhouse gas emissions by the equivalent of 0.75 million tonnes of carbon dioxide a year, although that has been disputed.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In 2011, the Treasury launched a consultation on potential revisions to Air Passenger Duty.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In their consultation they stated "Air passenger duty is primarily a revenue raising duty which makes an important contribution to the public finances, whilst also giving rise to secondary environmental benefits".
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Also in 2011, an alliance of business groups, airports, airlines, destinations and trade associations came together to form the campaign group 'A Fair Tax on Flying', calling for the Treasury to conduct a macro-economic impact-assessment of the tax, and to reform and reduce the tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The Chancellor's Autumn Statement, on 29 November 2011, announced an 8% increase in UK APD set for April 2012.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In 2013 a study by PwC, 'The Economic Impact of Air Passenger Duty', found that abolition of APD could provide an initial short-term boost to the level of UK GDP of around 0.45% in the first 12 months, averaging at just under 0.3% per annum between 2013 and 2015.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] It stated that this increase would permanently raise UK economic output, to the point where the economy could be up to £16 billion larger in the period 2013-15 than under the current system of APD.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In addition, it found that abolition would result in an increase in investment and exports, implying investment may rise by 6% in total between 2013 and 2015, with exports rising by 5% in the same period.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Almost 60,000 jobs could be created between 2013 and 2020, and although the abolition of APD would result in £3-4 billion in lost revenue to the Treasury, PwC's "cautious" analysis suggests that this would be offset by increased receipts from other taxes.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] At the 2014 Budget the Chancellor announced the removal of bands C and D of APD, coming into effect from 1 April 2015.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] It means that from 2015, the highest APD band levied was band B.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The tourist minister of Kenya, Najib Balala, criticised APD for hurting tourism and economy in developing countries.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In August 2015, Scottish Deputy First Minister John Swinney and Infrastructure Secretary Keith Brown jointly chaired the first meeting of the Scottish APD stakeholder forum to begin the process of designing and developing a Scottish APD.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] The devolution of APD to Scotland in the form of an Air Departure Tax was made possible by the Air Departure Tax (Scotland) Act 2017 which was passed on 20 June 2017 and received royal assent on 25 July 2017.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Once the process of devolving APD to Scotland was complete, the Scottish Government intended to reduce the rate by 50%, and eventually abolishing it completely once finances allow.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] Air Departure Tax was meant to be introduced to Scotland starting from 1 April 2018.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] However due to exemption of APD for flights departing from airports in the Highlands and Islands, the UK and Scottish governments agreed to delay the introduction of ADT, while sorting out the issues.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In June 2018, the Scottish and UK governments agreed it would not be possible to introduce ADT in April 2019.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] APD continues to apply to flights departing Scottish airports, and HMRC continues to have responsibility for administering APD in relation to Scottish flights, pending the resolution of the issues.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In 2019 the Scottish Government abandoned its plans to cut Air Departure Tax as the proposals were no longer considered compatible with Scotland's climate change targets.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In 2012 the Northern Ireland Assembly gained the power to adjust Air Passenger Duty, which it did through the **Air Passenger Duty (Setting of Rate) Act (Northern Ireland) 2012** (c.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] In June 2017 the Conservative Party and the Democratic Unionist Party agreed to review APD with regard to its possible reduction or abolition for Northern Ireland's airports.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-passenger-duty] APD on direct long-haul flights from Northern Ireland was cut to be the same rate as short-haul flights as of 1 November 2011, reducing the tax then on economy (coach) fares to the US from £60 to £12 and in premium classes (business and first) from £120 to £24.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] The **Air Travel Tax** (Irish: *Cáin Aerthaistil*) was an Irish tax applied to flights departing from airports in Ireland.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] Until 28 February 2011, there were two rates of tax, €10 for each passenger flying to an airport more than 300 km (186 miles) from Dublin Airport, and €2 per passenger flying to any other airport within 300 km (186 miles).
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] As the differential rate was considered by the EU to be an interference with the internal market, this was changed to a flat rate of €3 from 1 March 2011.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] The tax was opposed by airlines and the tourism industry.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] Initially the €10 tax was going to cover all flights over 300 km (186 miles), but this would have disadvantaged non-Dublin airports.
[src:air-departure-tax/air-travel-tax] Smaller airports are also excepted, of which only one has any scheduled flights to begin with; as are planes with fewer than 20 passenger seats.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] An **airport improvement fee** or **embarkation fee** or **airport tax** or **service charge** or **service fee** is an additional fee charged to departing and connecting passengers at an airport.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] It is levied by government or an airport management corporation and the proceeds are usually intended for funding of major airport improvements or expansion or airport service.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] Some airports do not levy these fees on connecting passengers who do not leave the airport or whose connecting flight is within a specific timeframe after they arrive.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] In the United States, the federal passenger facility charge (PFCs) program allows the collection of PFC fees up to $4.50 for every enplaned passenger at commercial airports controlled by public agencies.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] Airports use these fees to fund FAA-approved projects that enhance safety, security, or capacity; reduce noise; or increase air carrier competition.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] Federal law limits use of PFC funds strictly to the above categories.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] Depending on the location, the airport improvement fee is included in the cost of traveller's airline ticket, in which case the airline will forward the fee to proper agency.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] However, in some locations the fee must be paid at the point of embarkation.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] This often creates difficulties for departing passengers who are unfamiliar with this type of procedure, or for departing international passengers who have already exchanged all their local currency.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] The amount varies usually between US$10 and $30.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] In some instances, the fee continues to be charged long after construction has been completed (e.g.
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] Ottawa Macdonald–Cartier International Airport).
[src:air-departure-tax/airport-improvement-fee] A legitimate reason for this is that the airport must finance the cost of the improvement and then pays off these costs over an extended period of time.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Types of aviation taxation and subsidies, and implementations, are listed below.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Taxation is one of several methods to mitigate the environmental impact of aviation.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] According to the Amsterdam-based international environmental organisation Friends of the Earth (2005), aviation does not pay tax on fuel and aviation's expansion is fuelled by its exemption from taxes.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In the UK, aviation got £9 billion tax free benefits in 2003.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Friends of the Earth argued that fuel tax would give incentive to improve the energy efficiency of operations, and would be a more effective response than emission trading.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Chicago Convention prevents double taxation on aviation fuel on international flights, but does not prohibts it altogether.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Almost always taxes are exempt because of bilateral air agreements between countries.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] This is not always the case for domestic flights.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] For example, in the United States, on domestic flights fuel is taxed 19.3 cents per gallon on piston aviation fuel, 21.8 cents per gallon on JetA, and 4.3 cents per gallon on commercial jet fuel.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] This has been a very effective funding source for air traffic control without the complications and expenses of collecting on a per-flight basis.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Airlines are typically exempt from VAT, especially on international flights.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Historically, EU aviation fuel was tax free and attracted no VAT.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Commercial aviation fuel taxation in the EU was banned in 2003 by the Energy Taxation Directive (2003/96/EC), except with bilateral agreements between member states.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] However, as of 2018, no such agreements exist.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Citing the fact that aviation causes around 2.5% of global CO2 emissions, the Ministers proposed both uniform air passenger taxes as well as kerosene taxes (both excise duties and VAT).
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In a September–October 2019 poll conducted by the European Investment Bank (EIB) amongst 28,088 EU citizens from the then 28 member states, 72% said they would support a carbon tax on flights.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Austria introduced a Flight Tax Act (*Flugabgabegesetz*, *FlugAbgG*) in April 2011 similar to the German aviation taxation system.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In 2013, the fees for short and medium-haul flights were reduced from 8 euros to 7 euros and from 20 euros to 15 euros respectively, and halved again in 2018.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] During the COVID-19 pandemic, airlines in Europe had to temporarily cease most operations and had requested a total of 12.8 billion euros in government support by mid-April 2020, according to a Transport & Environment, Greenpeace and Carbon Market Watch report.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] On 8 June 2020, the Austrian conservative–green coalition government concluded a support deal for Austrian Airlines (a subsidiary of Lufthansa) for 150 million euros in taxpayer grants, and 300 million euros in banking loans that are to be paid back.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In 2022, the Belgian government introduced an aviation tax for all airline flights of 10 euros within 500 kilometres, two euros if the destination is located more than 500 kilometres away and within the EEA and four euros outside the EEA.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The reason the tax is higher for short flights is because a shift to trains is more realistic for those distances.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] On 9 July 2019, French transport minister Élisabeth Borne announced that France would introduce an eco-tax on passengers in 2020.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Flights within the EU, including domestic flights, would be taxed 1.5 euros for economy class and 9 euros for business class, while flights out of the EU would be charged with 3 euros for economy class and 18 euros for business class.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Different rules apply to Corsica and other overseas departments and territories of France.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The exo-tax was projected to produce 180 million euros in revenue annually.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] On 9 June 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic in France, economy and finance minister Bruno Le Maire announced a financial support programme for the aerospace sector for 15 billion euros.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] It included the earlier announced bailout of its flag carrier Air France–KLM at 7 billion euros (comprising a state loan of 3 billion and bank loans of 4 billion), with conditions to transform it into the 'most environmentally friendly airline on the planet'.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In 2018 Germany applied 19% VAT on domestic airline tickets.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Ireland had an Air Travel Tax from 2009 until April 2014.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] On 1 July 2008, the Fourth Balkenende cabinet introduced an aviation tax (*vliegbelasting* or *vliegtaks*) of 11.25 euros per ticket for flights within Europe and 45 euros for destinations outside Europe.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Due to vehement opposition by the aviation industry and travel agencies, the tax was abolished a year later on 1 July 2009, leading to heavy criticism from academia and environmental organisations.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol claimed it lost 900,000 passengers to airports abroad due to the tax, but Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam economist Eric Bartelsman pointed out that the Great Recession reduced air travel across the world, not just in the Netherlands.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Tilburg University economist Lans Bovenberg was more positive, arguing aviation taxes should be implemented simultaneously across the entire EU to be effective, and that taxing jet fuel would be a more effective measure than taxing passengers.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In 2017, the Third Rutte cabinet coalition agreement planned to introduce a new aviation tax of 7 euros on every ticket, regardless of destination, on 1 January 2021.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Cargo aircraft will pay a tax based on their weight and noise pollution class: up to 3.85 euros per tonne of cargo, with a lower rate for quieter aircraft.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The tax, which is projected to produce an annual revenue of 200 million euros, has four goals: reducing CO2 emissions, reducing other emissions such as particulates, reducing noise pollution, and preventing a jet fuel tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The new plan is more likely to succeed because the tax is much lower than in 2008, and most neighbouring countries except Belgium had also introduced aviation taxes in preceding years, making passengers' tax circumvention efforts unlikely.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The government was aiming to eventually establish a uniform EU-wide aviation tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Since 1 January 2021, an air passenger tax of €7.845 per person per flight applies in the Netherlands.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The tax does not apply to transfer passengers, and children under the age of 2.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In the Tax Plan 2023, the cabinet proposed to increase the air passenger tax by €18.48 from 2023.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Parliament had yet to approve the plans.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] 1 January 2023, the new tax rate of €26,43 went into force.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Sweden introduced a passenger tax for commercial flights of more than ten passengers in April 2018.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In November 2019, the Swedish government of Stefan Löven (Löfven I Cabinet) proposed to collect an annual aviation tax of around 78 million euros.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Under the proposal's conditions, the Swedish aviation industry would still be 100% exempt from the Swedish energy tax, carbon dioxide tax and sulphur tax that other companies pay.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Norway introduced airline passenger fees on 1 June 2016.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] From 1 June 2016 to 31 March 2020, the fee was 80 Norwegian kroner per passenger.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] On 1 April 2020, the fee was changed to 75 kroner for passengers with a final destination in Europe and 200 kroner for passengers with a final destination outside Europe.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The Swiss oil lobby started a campaign and a referendum against the new CO2 laws (which included the aviation tax), and in June 2021, 52% of the Swiss voters rejected them, meaning there will not be aviation taxes in the very near future.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Parliament continued to reject several parliamentary initiatives on the subject thereafter.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In the United States, most states tax avgas and jet fuel.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] Some governments subsidize airports and passenger customs costs within airports.
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] The EU Commission in 2014 ruled that subsidies Ryanair received from a regional authority a decade ago had to be repaid (€525,000).
[src:air-departure-tax/aviation-taxation-and-subsidies] In June 2020, Flemish Economy Minister Hilde Crevits decided that trainings for airplane and helicopter pilots would no longer be subsidised in Flanders from 1 July 2020 onwards.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] The Poor Law introduced in Scotland in 1579 provided for a poor rate to be levied to fund poor relief.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] The Poor Law (Scotland) Act 1845 modernized the system, and the Lands Valuation (Scotland) Act 1854 established the foundations of the modern system.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] The Valuation and Rating (Scotland) Act 1956 established a system of five-yearly revaluations, undertaken by an Assessor appointed by the local authority.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] In 1989, domestic properties were removed from the rating system with the introduction of the Community Charge in Scotland, later to be replaced with Council Tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] The Local Government Finance Act 1988 amended the existing rating system in Scotland from 1990 at the same time as introducing a new system of business rates in England and Wales from 1990, and the Local Government Finance Act 1992 made further changes.
[src:air-departure-tax/business-rates-in-scotland] While the latter two acts applied to the whole of the United Kingdom, as the Scottish system is based on Scots law, it remains fundamentally different from the system in England and Wales.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each piece of legislation passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom ("Westminster") is known as an **act of Parliament**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each modern act of Parliament has a **title** (also known as a "**long title**") and a **short title**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] A short title provides a convenient name for referring to an individual Act, such as "Jamaica Independence Act 1962".
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The long title is more comprehensive in scope, providing a sometimes very detailed description of the act's provisions that is too unwieldy for convenient citation; for example, the long title of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 is around 400 words.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts are today split between three series, **public general acts**, **local acts**, and **personal acts**, and cited accordingly.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each act within each series is numbered sequentially with a **chapter number**, identifying it as a chapter of the (notional) statute book.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Since 1 January 1963, chapter numbers in each series are organised by **calendar year**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The first public general act passed in a year is "c.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] 2", and so on; the first local act of a year is "c. i", the second is "c. ii", and so on; while the first personal act of a year is "c.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] *2*", and so on (note the use of italics).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Chapter numbers for acts passed before the Acts of Parliament Numbering and Citation Act 1962 are not by calendar year, but instead by the year(s) of the reign during which the relevant parliamentary session was held; thus the Jamaica Independence Act 1962 is cited as "10 & 11 Eliz.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] 40", meaning the 40th (public) act passed during the session that started in the 10th year of the reign of Elizabeth II and which finished in the 11th year of that reign.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] 2* – is an Arabic rather than a Roman numeral, although historically this was not the case.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Earlier practice was to specify the parliamentary session by the year in which it *started* only – and sometimes to date its acts accordingly.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] So, for example, the Adventurers' Act was passed by the session 16 Cha.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] In consequence the act is often referred to as the Adventurers' Act 1640: despite being passed in response to events in 1641.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Short titles were only introduced in the middle of the 19th century, and it was only by the late 1890s that every individual act of Parliament had one.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Older acts may also have a "conventional" short title, such as "Crewe's Act".
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The Parliament of the United Kingdom came into being on 1 January 1801; before that date, legislation was passed either by the Parliament of Great Britain or the Parliament of Ireland.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Similarly, the Parliament of Great Britain came into being on 1 May 1707 (OS); before that date, legislation was passed either by the Parliament of England or the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts passed by each of these parliaments, except for the Parliament of Scotland, are cited in the same way as pre-1963 acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom; i.e., by parliamentary session and chapter number.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts passed by the Parliament of Scotland are cited by calendar year and chapter number.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts of the last session of the Parliament of Great Britain and the first session of the Parliament of the United Kingdom are both cited as "41 Geo.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The numbering runs straight through, effectively merging the sessions: that is, the numbers for the Parliament of Great Britain's acts continue unbroken from the numbers for the Parliament of England's.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Some individual acts from these parliaments have more than one citation, depending on the edition in which the act is printed.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Modern practice for the parliaments of England and Great Britain is to follow the citations used in *The Statutes of the Realm*, while for Scotland the citations used are those in *The Acts of the Parliaments of Scotland* (both of which are considered legally authoritative).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] These latter citations are also used in the official *Chronological Table of the Statutes*.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Only a small number of acts passed by these parliaments have been given a short title by later legislation.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] All legislation passed by the various devolved parliaments and assemblies has both a short title and a long title.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each piece of legislation passed by the former Parliament of Northern Ireland (Stormont) was also known as an **act of Parliament**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] There is a difference in naming convention between acts passed in Northern Ireland and acts passed at Westminster but relating to Northern Ireland.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Thus, the Criminal Evidence Act (Northern Ireland) 1923 is an act passed at Stormont, but the Criminal Appeal (Northern Ireland) Act 1930 is an act passed at Westminster (note the different placement of "(Northern Ireland)" in the two).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts of the Northern Ireland Assembly are cited by calendar year and chapter number; e.g. the Autism Act (Northern Ireland) 2011 is "2011 c.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts of the Scottish Parliament are cited by calendar year and the acronymic "asp" number ; e.g., the Abolition of Feudal Tenure etc.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Measures of the National Assembly for Wales (2003–2011) are cited by calendar year and the acronymic "nawm" number; e.g., the Welsh Language (Wales) Measure 2011 is "2011 nawm 1" ("*2011 mccc 1*" in Welsh).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts of the National Assembly for Wales (2012–2020) are cited by calendar year and acronymic "anaw" number; e.g. the National Assembly for Wales (Official Languages) Act 2012 is "2012 anaw 1" ("*2012 dccc 1*" in Welsh).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Acts of the Senedd Cymru (2020–) are cited by calendar year and acronymic "asc" number; e.g. the Wild Animals and Circuses (Wales) Act 2020 is "2020 asc 2" ("*2020 dsc 2*" in Welsh).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Measures passed by the General Synod of the Church of England (formerly the Church Assembly) follow the numbering conventions used for Westminster legislation, except that each measure has a "number" rather than a chapter number.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] For example, the New Parishes Measure 1943 is cited as "6 & 7 Geo.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] With the exception of Northern Ireland secondary legislation, each piece of secondary legislation made in the United Kingdom since 1948 has been numbered as a **statutory instrument** (or **SI**).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Most individual SIs have what is generally referred to as a "short title" (despite none having a "long title").
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each SI is centrally registered and issued with a number; the numbering resumes from "1" at the start of each calendar year.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Thus, the Northern Ireland Negotiations (Referendum) Order 1998 is cited as "SI 1998 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Commencement orders are also numbered separately as part of a "C." sub-series; this number is appended to the main number.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Statutory Instruments relating to Scotland were similarly numbered as part of an "S." sub-series until the series of Scottish statutory instruments began (for which, see below).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The system for **statutory rules and orders** in place from 1894 to 1947 was less comprehensive.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] However, those instruments centrally registered and issued with a number follow the same pattern; thus the Trinidad and Tobago (Constitution) Order in Council 1950 is numbered as "SI 1950 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The annual volumes of SIs before 1961, and all those for SR&Os, were organised by subject matter rather than by instrument number.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] This means that these instruments should ideally be cited by both number and page reference; thus the full citation for the Trinidad and Tobago (Constitution) Order in Council 1950 would be "SI 1950 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Some **prerogative instruments** are also printed in appendices to the annual volumes of SIs.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] These instruments are not numbered, and are thus cited by page number only; e.g., the Fiji (Appeal to Privy Council) Order in Council 1950 is cited as "SI 1950 Vol.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Older secondary legislation frequently lacks a short title.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] An example of an incorrect citation as a result of this can be found in regulation 3 of the Cremation (Amendment) Regulations 2006 (SI 2006/92).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] This longer form of citation was used when the 1930 regulations were revoked by schedule 2 to the Cremation (England and Wales) Regulations 2008 (SI 2008/2841).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] A statutory instrument made by the Scottish Government is called a **Scottish statutory instrument** (or **SSI**).
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each of these is separately numbered, with the numbering resuming from "No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] 1" at the start of each calendar year; thus the Radioactive Substances Exemption (Scotland) Order 2011 is cited as "SSI 2011 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] A statutory instrument made by the Welsh Government is called a **Welsh statutory instrument**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each of these is numbered as part of the sequence of UK SIs but is also numbered separately as part of a "W." series, with the numbering resuming from "W.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Thus, the Isle of Anglesey (Electoral Arrangements) Order 2012 is cited as "SI 2012 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Statutory instruments made by Order in Council as primary legislation for Northern Ireland are numbered as part of the main UK series of SIs, but are also numbered separately as part of an "NI" series, with the numbering resuming from "NI 1" at the start of each calendar year.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Legislation passed by the Northern Ireland Assembly cites these instruments by the "NI" number only.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Secondary legislation made by the Northern Ireland Executive is numbered sequentially as part of the **statutory rules of Northern Ireland**, with the numbering resuming from "No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The numbering mirrors that used for the UK's main series of SIs; thus the Prohibition of Traffic (Ardoyne, Belfast) Order (Northern Ireland) 2011 is cited as "SR 2011 No.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Previously this type of secondary legislation was numbered as "Statutory Rules and Orders (Northern Ireland)".
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each distinct "enactment" within an act of Parliament is called a **section** (abbreviated "s.", plural "ss.").
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Each section has a distinct number, in continual sequence from "s.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] If a section is subdivided or has subordinate elements, then these are known as subsections, each of which has a bracketed number; e.g., "s.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Subsections are subdivided in turn into paragraphs, which are identified by an italicised letter; e.g., "s.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Subparagraphs are identified with lower-case Roman numerals; e.g., "s.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The section sign is not used in citation.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] In schedules to an act of Parliament, each distinct numbered element is called a **paragraph** (abbreviated "para."), which is subdivided in turn into subparagraphs.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The sections within a lengthy or complex act are sometimes grouped together for convenience to form a **Part**.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] A "Part" may in turn be subdivided into "chapters".
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Other groupings are occasionally found as well.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] When an amendment to an act requires the insertion of a new section part of the way through a numerical sequence, then sequential capital letters are used following the appropriate number; thus, a new section inserted between s.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The terminology for the structure of acts and measures of the devolved parliaments and assemblies follows that used for Westminster legislation.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] During its passage through the Westminster Parliament, each proposed enactment forming part of a bill is known as a **clause**, rather than as a section.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] For Scottish legislation, the term "section" is used for bills as for acts of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The terminology used for the equivalent in secondary legislation of sections of an act of Parliament depends upon the particular type of instrument; however, the numbering system follows the same pattern.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] A comparison of terms and abbreviations is shown in the table below.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] The naming and citation of provisions included in a schedule is the same across all forms of legislation as the system used for Westminster legislation, and has therefore been omitted from this table.
[src:air-departure-tax/citation-of-united-kingdom-legislation] Section 19(1)(b) refers to the edition commonly known as *The Statutes of the Realm*.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Council Tax is collected by local authorities though part of the tax goes to Scottish Water for water and sewage services.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] In general terms: The occupiers of a property are liable, regardless of tenure, or the owners if the property is unoccupied, except if the property is a 'house in multiple occupation', in which case the landlord is liable for paying the Council Tax.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Each dwelling is allocated to one of eight bands coded by letters A to H on the basis of its assumed capital value as of 1 April 1991 and newer properties than this are assigned a nominal 1991 value.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Assessment of property values is performed by the Assessor appointed by each local authority; in some cases there is a valuation joint board that covers multiple council areas.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Each local authority sets a tax rate expressed as the annual levy on a Band D property inhabited by two liable adults.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] This decision automatically sets the amounts levied on all types of households and dwellings.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] The *nominal Band D* property total is calculated by adding together the number of properties in each band and multiplying by the band ratio.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] So 100 Band D properties will count as 100 *nominal Band D* properties, whereas 100 Band C properties will count as 89 *nominal Band D* properties.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Each collecting authority then adds together the Band D amounts for their area (or subdivisions of their area in the case, for example, of civil parish council precepts) to reach a total Band D council tax bill.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] To calculate the council tax for a particular property a ratio is then applied.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] A Band D property will pay the full amount, whereas a Band H property will pay 245% of that figure.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Under Scottish Law, it is the responsibility of the tax payer to prove that the tax has been paid, not for the council to prove that it has not.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] John Wilson MSP presented an Enforcement of Local Tax Arrears (Scotland) Bill on 19 March 2010 in order to try to reduce this collection time from 20 to 5 years.
[src:air-departure-tax/council-tax-in-scotland] Although Wilson's bill has not made any progress (as of October 2016), the Scottish parliament has passed the Community Charge Debt (Scotland) Bill to stop Councils pursuing debts from the older Community Charge, though there are some scrutiny stages to go through before it can become law.
